Before you start ...¶

There is a problem in the data file CroqPain.parquet (i.e., the data needs some 'cleaning'). Find the issue and propose a fix before you continue with the analysis.

  • Hint: Check data histograms

Post questions on Piazza as needed. Discuss your "fix" with the TAs during a work session or post your proposed data "fix" on Piazza as a private post. Apply your fix and "store" it into a dataset called CroqPainFix.

Goal¶

  • build a regression model to forecast earnings (EARN) for potential new outlets based on the data from the existing 60 stores.

The predictors in this model could be¶

  • capital (K),
  • store size (SIZE),
  • demographic factors (P15, P25, P35, P45, P55, total),
  • average income (INC),
  • competition factors (COMP, NCOMP, NREST),
  • rent price (PRICE),
  • cost of living index (CLI).

# For right-skewed data ('K' and 'PRICE'), Box-Cox transformation
# Box-Cox requires all values to be positive, so add a small value to avoid zero or negative values
df_transformed['K_boxcox'], _ = boxcox(df['K'] + 0.01)  
df_transformed['PRICE_boxcox'], _ = boxcox(df['PRICE'] + 0.01)

# For left-skewed data ('CLI'), we use a reflection (subtracting from a constant) and then log transformation
max_cli = df['CLI'].max() + 1  
df_transformed['CLI_reflected_log'] = np.log(max_cli - df['CLI'])

# Plotting histograms after further transformations
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))

def detect_and_remove_outliers(df, column):
    Q1 = df[column].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = df[column].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

    outliers = df[(df[column] < lower_bound) | (df[column] > upper_bound)]
    cleaned_df = df[(df[column] >= lower_bound) & (df[column] <= upper_bound)]

    return outliers, cleaned_df

# Example usage for 'EARN'
outliers, df_cleaned = detect_and_remove_outliers(df_transformed, 'EARN')

When you run regressions, be sure to use the VIF feature in Radiant for a more rigorous evaluation of multicollinearity. As you are building a model, it can also be useful to examine standardized coefficients. If interested, you can experiment with the Stepwise selection option in the Summary tab (i.e., click the checkbox) in the R version of Radiant (launched from RStudio). My Takeaway¶

  • Small Sample Size: With only 62 data points, this model may not have enough information to capture the true relationships between the variables effectively. Small datasets can lead to higher variability and less reliable estimates, impacting the model's ability to explain the variance in the dependent variable.

  • R-squared (0.206): Indicates that about 20.6% of the variability in EARN_total is explained by the model. This is relatively low, suggesting that the model does not explain a large portion of the variance in the response variable.

  • NREST_total is statistically significant (p-value = 0.021), implying that it has a meaningful relationship with EARN_total.

  • P15_total has a coefficient of 56.28, suggesting that a one-unit increase in P15_total is associated with an increase of 56.28 units in EARN_total.
